example.p:
In \mathbb{Z}_3[x], if f(x) = 1+x and g(x) = 2+x, then \begin{split} f(x) + g(x) &= (1+x) + (2+x)\\ & = \left(1 +_3 2\right)+ \left(1 +_3 1\right) x\\ & = 0 + 2x \\ & = 2x \end{split}
and \begin{split} f(x)g(x) &= (1+x) \cdot (2 +x) \\ &= 1\times_3 2+ (1 \times_3 1 +_3 1 \times_3 2)x^2 + (1 \times_3 2)x^2\\ & =2 + 0 x + x^2\\ & =2 + x^2\\ \end{split}
However, for the same polynomials as above, f(x) and g(x) in the more familiar setting of \mathbb{Z}[x], we have f(x) + g(x) = (1+x) + (2+x) = (1 +2)+ (1 +1) x = 3 + 2x and \begin{split}f(x)g(x) =(1+x)\cdot(2 +x)\\ & = 1\cdot 2+ (1 \cdot 1 + 1 \cdot 2)x + (1 \cdot 1)x^2\\ & = 2 +3x + x^2\\ \end{split}

answer.p:
Induction: Assume that for some n\geq 0, S(k) is true for all k \leq  n, If f(x) has degree n+1, then there are two cases to
consider. If \deg  g(x) > n + 1, f(x) = g(x)\cdot 0 + f(x), and we are done. Otherwise, if \deg  g(x) =m \leq  n + 1, we perform long
division as follows, where LDT's stand for terms of lower degree than n+1.
\begin{array}{rll}
   & f_{n+1}\cdot g_m{}^{-1}x^{n+1-m} \\
 g_mx^m+ \textrm{ LDT}'s & \overline{\left) f_{n+1}x^{n+1}\right.+ \textrm{ LDT}'s 
\textrm{                     }}& \\ & \underline{\textrm{    }f_{n+1}x^{n+1}+ \textrm{ LDT}'s}\textrm{ 
                             }\\& \quad\quad\quad\quad\quad h(x) \\
\end{array}
